Tags.Description: Kronos steals credentials and uses Web injects made for every major browser to modify legitimate banking websites. Kronos comes with a Ring3 rootkit to help defend it against other Trojans.

Malicious software is often injected into legitimate running processes on affected systems to make identification and recovery of the malware more difficult.  There are a wide variety of mechanisms for injecting code, and more often than not this is indicative of malicious activity that warrants further investigation.

The sample contacted an IP address info service via HTTP. This is often used malware to tailor a message or note to the compromised system in a user's language by geographic IP location. This behavior is also used often used by malware to identify sandboxes to prevent executing in a lab environment.

Malware authors learned long ago that performing a ping, often against the localhost IP address of 1.1.1.1, takes approximately one second to accomplish. As such, malware authors will often execute a series of pings as an alternative to calling a sleep function, or in situations where no such function exists.
These are samples which reach out to the Tor Consensus server. The Tor Consensus server is able to verify which IP addresses are valid tor nodes.

Samples exhibiting this behaviour connect to an entire .0/24 which indicates they are attempting to scan a given network range.

Sometimes this tag will match on files which perform wide ranging scanning against large numbers of non-sequential IPs.
These files attempt to access the locally keys used to encrypt passwords stored locally in order to decrypt them.
RedLine Stealer is a .NET based information stealer initially revealed by Proofpoint in March of 2020. It features a robust server-side backend and leverages SOAP for C2.
